{"title_page": "Peter Snow (doctor)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Peter Snow\n| image       =Peter Snow (doctor).jpg\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = 1935\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|df=yes|2006|2|28|1935}}\n| death_place =\n| nationality = {{NZL}}\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| occupation  = physician\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n'''Dr Peter Snow''' (1935&nbsp;\u2013 28 February 2006) was a [[general practitioner]] who served the [[New Zealand]] rural community of [[Tapanui]] for over 30 years. He was president of the Royal New Zealand College of GPs from 1998\u201399 and received their highest honour, Distinguished Fellowship, in 2001.<ref name=\"Scoop\">{{cite web |last=Fox |first= Jonathan|coauthors= |title= New Zealand loses a fine GP|url= http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/GE0603/S00010.htm|date= 2009-09-02|work=Scoop|publisher= Scoop.co.nz|accessdate=27 August 2009}}</ref> He was a member of the Otago Hospital Board and its successor, the District Health Board.<ref name=\"Scoop\"/>\n\n==Education==\nAs a boy Peter Grahame Snow attended [[Auckland Grammar School]], graduating with the class of 1948.<ref name=\"RNZCGP Annual Report\">{{cite web|title=Peter Snow obituary |url=http://www.rnzcgp.org.nz/documents/ANNUAL_REPORT_2006.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061007204023/http://www.rnzcgp.org.nz/documents/ANNUAL_REPORT_2006.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 October 2006 |page=37 |work=Annual Report 2006 |publisher=Royal New Zealand College of General Practitioners |accessdate=3 March 2006 }}</ref>\n\nWhile training in medicine he intended to become a surgeon, but was unable to do so because he wore glasses to correct his eyesight, so he took up general practice in Tapanui.\n\n==Practice==\nIn 1984 he was presented with a number of patients with a prolonged [[Exercise intolerance|exertional]] [[Influenza|'flu]]-like illness, but presenting no diagnosable condition.<ref name=\"RNZCGP Annual Report\"/>  While some people thought they were no different from commonly found \"[[Fatigue (medical)|tired all the time]]\" (TATT) cases, Dr Snow was convinced that they were indeed sick and proceeded to investigate. Many were sheep farmers who previously had a perfect record of health.  Observing a similarity between the symptoms of stock suffering from [[Selenium#Selenium and health|selenium deficiency]] and these patients, he was the first doctor in New Zealand to identify the disease which turned out to be an outbreak of [[myalgic encephalomyelitis]], now classed as [[chronic fatigue syndrome]].<ref name=\"Scoop\"/><ref name=\"NZFP\">{{cite web |last= Snow|first= Peter|coauthors= |title= Reminiscences of the chronic fatigue syndrome|url= http://www.rnzcgp.org.nz/assets/teach_prac/NZFP/Dec2002/Snow-December-02.pdf|date= December 2002|work= New Zealand Family Physician|publisher= The Royal New Zealand College of General Practitioners|accessdate=27 August 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> Due to, often disparaging, publicity surrounding these discoveries and a study into them by Peter Snow, Marion Poore, and Charlotte Paul, the illness came to be known in New Zealand as \"[[Tapanui|Tapanui flu]]\" after the town of the same name in West Otago.<ref name=\"NZFP\"/>\n\nDr Snow also became concerned at the number of farmers injured in farm accidents, particularly those involving motorcycles, and made recommendations for improving farm safety. He campaigned unsuccessfully to prevent the closure of the Tapanui hospital, at which he was on call 24 hours a day, 7 days a week.<ref name=\"Scoop\"/><ref name=\"Memorial1\">{{cite web |last=Matangi |first= Tuangane|coauthors= |title= Moon rock memorial for doctor unveiled|url= http://www.odt.co.nz/the-regions/southland/69867/moon-rock-memorial-doctor-unveiled|date= 2009-08-12|work= Otago Daily Times |publisher= Allied Press Limited|accessdate=27 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement, death and legacy==\nAfter more than thirty years in Tapanui, Peter Snow and his wife retired to [[Lake Hayes, New Zealand|Lake Hayes]]. Peter Snow died on 28 February 2006.<ref name=\"RNZCGP Annual Report\"/> A memorial to Dr Snow, comprising a moon rock and plaque was unveiled in the main street of Tapanui on Saturday 8 August 2009. The moon rock was chosen because of Dr Snows belief that a meteor had collided with the moon in 1766 and dispersed debris across West Otago.<ref name=\"Memorial1\"/><ref name=\"Memorial2\">{{cite web |last= Conway|first= Glenn |coauthors= |title= Tapanui District remembers a GP of significance|url= http://www.odt.co.nz/the-regions/south-otago/69085/tapanui-district-remembers-a-gp-significance|date= 2009-08-10|work= Otago Daily Times |publisher= Allied Press Limited|accessdate=27 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Snow, Peter}}\n[[Category:1935 births]]\n[[Category:2006 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Auckland Grammar School]]\n[[Category:New Zealand general practitioners]]\n[[Category:Members of district health boards in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Peter Snow\n| image       =Peter Snow (doctor).jpg\n| image_size  =\n| alt         =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = 1935\n| birth_place =\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|df=yes|2006|2|28|1935}}\n| death_place =\n| nationality = {{NZL}}\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| occupation  = physician\n}}{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n'''Dr Peter Snow''' (1935&nbsp;\u2013 28 February 2006) was a [[general practitioner]] who served the [[New Zealand]] rural community of [[Tapanui]] for over 30 years. He was president of the Royal New Zealand College of GPs from 1998\u201399 and received their highest honour, Distinguished Fellowship, in 2001.<ref name=\"Scoop\">{{cite web |last=Fox |first= Jonathan|coauthors= |title= New Zealand loses a fine GP|url= http://www.scoop.co.nz/stories/GE0603/S00010.htm|date= 2009-09-02|work=Scoop|publisher= Scoop.co.nz|accessdate=27 August 2009}}</ref> He was a member of the Otago Hospital Board and its successor, the District Health Board.<ref name=\"Scoop\"/>\n\n==Education==\nAs a boy Peter Grahame Snow attended [[Auckland Grammar School]], graduating with the class of 1948.<ref name=\"RNZCGP Annual Report\">{{cite web|title=Peter Snow obituary |url=http://www.rnzcgp.org.nz/documents/ANNUAL_REPORT_2006.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061007204023/http://www.rnzcgp.org.nz/documents/ANNUAL_REPORT_2006.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=7 October 2006 |page=37 |work=Annual Report 2006 |publisher=Royal New Zealand College of General Practitioners |accessdate=3 March 2006 }}</ref>\n\nWhile training in medicine he intended to become a surgeon, but was unable to do so because he wore glasses to correct his eyesight, so he took up general practice in Tapanui.\n\n==Practice==\nIn 1984 he was presented with a number of patients with a prolonged [[Exercise intolerance|exertional]] [[Influenza|'flu]]-like illness, but presenting no diagnosable condition.<ref name=\"RNZCGP Annual Report\"/>  While some people thought they were no different from commonly found \"[[Fatigue (medical)|tired all the time]]\" (TATT) cases, Dr Snow was convinced that they were indeed sick and proceeded to investigate. Many were sheep farmers who previously had a perfect record of health.  Observing a similarity between the symptoms of stock suffering from [[Selenium#Selenium and health|selenium deficiency]] and these patients, he was the first doctor in New Zealand to identify the disease which turned out to be an outbreak of [[myalgic encephalomyelitis]], now classed as [[chronic fatigue syndrome]].<ref name=\"Scoop\"/><ref name=\"NZFP\">{{cite web |last= Snow|first= Peter|coauthors= |title= Reminiscences of the chronic fatigue syndrome|url= http://www.rnzcgp.org.nz/assets/teach_pr